title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a field. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(\mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Let
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[I_{X}=\{p\in \mathbb {F}[x]\mid  p(X)=0\},]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(X)=0]]></fr:tex> is the zero matrix, and we see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I_{X}]]></fr:tex> is a proper ideal of the principal ideal domain <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a unique monic polynomial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{X}(x)\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I_{X}=(m_{X}(x))]]></fr:tex>. We call this <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{X}(x)]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Minimal Polynomial of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex></html:dfn>.</fr:p>
 
   
